def perform_regression_polynomial(df, y, treatment, base_var, cluster, poly_degree=0):
    # Base formula includes only the treatment variable for pol0
    formula = f"{y} ~ {treatment}"
    
    # Conditionally add polynomial terms and their interactions if poly_degree > 0
    if poly_degree > 0:
        for i in range(1, poly_degree + 1):
            poly_term = f"np.power({base_var}, {i})"
            interaction_term = f"{poly_term} * {treatment}"
            formula += f" + {poly_term} + {interaction_term}"
    
    # Fitting the model with cluster-robust standard errors
    model = smf.ols(formula, data=df).fit(cov_type='cluster', cov_kwds={'groups': df[cluster]})
    return model

# Example usage for polynomial degrees 0, 1, 2, and 3
model_pol0 = perform_regression_polynomial(df, 'INVSALES', 'treat', 's', 'score', poly_degree=0)
print("Polynomial Degree 0:\n", model_pol0.summary())

model_pol1 = perform_regression_polynomial(df, 'INVSALES', 'treat', 's', 'score', poly_degree=1)
print("\nPolynomial Degree 1:\n", model_pol1.summary())

model_pol2 = perform_regression_polynomial(df, 'INVSALES', 'treat', 's', 'score', poly_degree=2)
print("\nPolynomial Degree 2:\n", model_pol2.summary())

model_pol3 = perform_regression_polynomial(df, 'INVSALES', 'treat', 's', 'score', poly_degree=3)

# Function to plot sharp RDD lines
def plot_sharp_rdd(df, metric, cutoff=75, title='', xlabel='Score', ylabel='Investment/Sales'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    
    # Scatter plot
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='score', y=metric, alpha=0.6, edgecolor=None)
    
    # Split data at the cutoff
    left_of_cutoff = df[df['score'] < cutoff]
    right_of_cutoff = df[df['score'] >= cutoff]
    
    # Fit linear models on either side of the cutoff
    model_left = smf.ols(f'{metric} ~ score', data=left_of_cutoff).fit()
    model_right = smf.ols(f'{metric} ~ score', data=right_of_cutoff).fit()
    
    # Generate predictions based on the models
    score_left = np.linspace(left_of_cutoff['score'].min(), cutoff, 100)
    score_right = np.linspace(cutoff, right_of_cutoff['score'].max(), 100)
    
    pred_left = model_left.predict(exog=dict(score=score_left))
    pred_right = model_right.predict(exog=dict(score=score_right))
    
    # Plotting the fitted lines
    plt.plot(score_left, pred_left, color='blue', linewidth=2)
    plt.plot(score_right, pred_right, color='red', linewidth=2)
    
    # Highlight the cutoff
    plt.axvline(x=cutoff, color='green', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
    
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.grid(True, which='both', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Assuming 'df' is your DataFrame
# Plotting for each investment metric with sharp RDD lines
plot_sharp_rdd(df, 'INVSALES', title='Panel A: Total Investment/Sales')
plot_sharp_rdd(df, 'INVTSALES', title='Panel B: Tangible Investment/Sales')
plot_sharp_rdd(df, 'INVINTSALES', title='Panel C: Intangible Investment/Sales')

# Function to perform regression with additional variables for small and large firms
def perform_regression_firm_size(df, y, cluster, controls, condition=None):
    formula = f"{y} ~ {' + '.join(controls)}"
    if condition is not None:
        df_filtered = df.query(condition)
    else:
        df_filtered = df
    model = smf.ols(formula, data=df_filtered).fit(cov_type='cluster', cov_kwds={'groups': df_filtered[cluster]})
    return model

# Full sample regression examples
controls_full_sample = ['largem', 'treatsmall', 'treatlarge', 'ssmall', 'slarge', 'streatsmall', 'streatlarge']
model_full_sample = perform_regression_firm_size(df, 'INVSALES', 'score', controls_full_sample)
print("Full Sample Regression:\n", model_full_sample.summary())

# Local estimates regression example (e.g., for 50% around cutoff)
condition_50 = "score > 51 & score < 81"
model_local_50 = perform_regression_firm_size(df, 'INVSALES', 'score', controls_full_sample, condition=condition_50)
print("\nLocal Estimates 50% Regression:\n", model_local_50.summary())

# Adjust the controls list and conditions for different polynomial degrees and local estimates as needed.

def plot_figure_3(df, y, title, xlabel='Score', ylabel='Investment/Pre-Program Sales'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='score', y=y, alpha=0.5)
    
    # Fit and plot a regression line for the range below the cutoff
    sns.regplot(data=df[df['score'] < 75], x='score', y=y, scatter=False, color='blue', order=3, ci=None)
    
    # Fit and plot a regression line for the range above the cutoff
    sns.regplot(data=df[df['score'] >= 75], x='score', y=y, scatter=False, color='red', order=3, ci=None)
    
    plt.axvline(x=75, color='green', linestyle='--')  # Cutoff line
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()
# Replace 'df' with your DataFrame variable name
plot_figure_3(df, 'INVSALES', 'Panel A. Total Investment/Pre-Program Sales')
plot_figure_3(df, 'INVTSALES', 'Panel B. Tangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales')
plot_figure_3(df, 'INVINTSALES', 'Panel C. Intangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales')

def plot_rdd_figure_4(df, metric, title, cutoff=75, xlabel='Score', ylabel='Investment/Pre-Program Sales'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    
    # Scatter plot of the investment metric against the score
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='score', y=metric, alpha=0.5)
    
    # Fit regression models on either side of the cutoff and plot
    for side, color in [('score < @cutoff', 'blue'), ('score >= @cutoff', 'red')]:
        subset = df.query(side)
        model = smf.ols(f'{metric} ~ score', data=subset).fit()
        sns.lineplot(x=subset['score'], y=model.predict(subset), color=color, label=f'Fit for {side}')
    
    # Highlight the cutoff
    plt.axvline(x=cutoff, color='green', linestyle='--', label='Cutoff')
    
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Plotting the figures for total, tangible, and intangible investment relative to pre-program sales
plot_rdd_figure_4(df, 'INVSALES', 'Figure 4, Panel A: Total Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')
plot_rdd_figure_4(df, 'INVTSALES', 'Figure 4, Panel B: Tangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')
plot_rdd_figure_4(df, 'INVINTSALES', 'Figure 4, Panel C: Intangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')

# Function to plot the RDD for small firms focusing on pre-program investment
def plot_figure_5(df, metric, title, cutoff=75, xlabel='Score', ylabel='Investment/Pre-Program Sales'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    
    # Scatter plot for visualization
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='score', y=metric, alpha=0.5)
    
    # Fit linear regression models for data points on each side of the cutoff
    for condition, color in [('score < @cutoff', 'blue'), ('score >= @cutoff', 'red')]:
        data_subset = df.query(condition)
        model = smf.ols(f'{metric} ~ score', data=data_subset).fit()
        sns.lineplot(x=data_subset['score'], y=model.predict(data_subset), color=color, label=f'Fit for {condition}')
    
    # Cutoff visualization
    plt.axvline(x=cutoff, color='green', linestyle='--', label='Cutoff')
    
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Assuming 'df' is your DataFrame containing the dataset
# Generate plots for each metric
plot_figure_5(df, 'INVSALES', 'Figure 5, Panel A: Total Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')
plot_figure_5(df, 'INVTSALES', 'Figure 5, Panel B: Tangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')
plot_figure_5(df, 'INVINTSALES', 'Figure 5, Panel C: Intangible Investment/Pre-Program Sales for Small Firms')
